  "prompt": "Why do I have red itchy balls all over my skin?",
  "response": "Red, itchy bumps all over your skin can be caused by a variety of things. Here are some possibilities, ranging from common to less common:\n\n**Common Causes:**\n\n*   **Hives (Urticaria):** These are raised, itchy welts that can appear anywhere on the body. They're often caused by an allergic reaction to food, medication, insect bites, or other triggers. They can come and go quickly.\n\n*   **Eczema (Atopic Dermatitis):** This is a chronic skin condition that causes dry, itchy, inflamed skin. It often appears in patches.\n\n*   **Heat Rash (Miliaria):** This occurs when sweat ducts get blocked and sweat becomes trapped under the skin. It's common in hot, humid weather and looks like small, red bumps.\n\n*   **Folliculitis:** This is an inflammation of hair follicles, often caused by bacteria. It can look like small, red bumps with a white center. Shaving, waxing, or wearing tight clothing can contribute.\n\n*   **Insect Bites (Mosquitoes, Fleas, Bedbugs):** These bites can cause small, red, itchy bumps. Bedbug bites often appear in a line or cluster.\n\n*   **Contact Dermatitis:** This is an allergic reaction or irritation caused by something that comes into contact with your skin, such as poison ivy, detergents, soaps, or lotions.\n\n**Less Common Causes:**\n\n*   **Chickenpox:** If you haven't had chickenpox or the vaccine, this is a possibility. It starts with small, itchy red bumps that turn into blisters.\n\n*   **Shingles:** A reactivation of the chickenpox virus, causing a painful rash with blisters, usually on one side of the body.\n\n*   **Measles:** A highly contagious viral infection that starts with a fever, cough, and runny nose, followed by a rash of small, red spots.\n\n*   **Scabies:** An infestation of tiny mites that burrow into the skin, causing intense itching, especially at night. It often affects the areas between fingers, wrists, and genitals.\n\n**Important Considerations:**\n\n*   **Other Symptoms:** Do you have a fever, cough, runny nose, body aches, or other symptoms? This information can help narrow down the possibilities.\n*   **Recent Exposures:** Have you been exposed to anything new, such as a new detergent, lotion, or food? Have you been in contact with someone who has a rash?\n*   **Progression:** How long have you had the rash? Is it spreading? Are the bumps changing in appearance?\n*   **Itch Intensity:** Is the itching mild, moderate, or severe? Does anything make it better or worse?\n\n**What You Should Do:**\n\n1.  **Avoid Scratching:** Scratching can make the rash worse and increase the risk of infection.\n\n2.  **Take a Photo:** Take a clear photo of the rash to show a doctor if needed.\n\n3.  **See a Doctor (Highly Recommended):** **The best course of action is to see a doctor or dermatologist.** They can properly diagnose the cause of your rash and recommend the appropriate treatment. Skin conditions can look very similar, and a proper diagnosis is essential. Don't try to self-diagnose or self-treat without professional guidance.\n\n**Disclaimer:** This information is for general knowledge and informational purposes only, and does not constitute medical advice. It is essential to consult with a qualified healthcare professional for any health concerns or before making any decisions related to your health or treatment.\n",
